Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. records.addlTxt:
10:37 AM; Case called for Hearing. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Nikole Kane.  Defendant Christine Van Brocklin in court.  Attorney Jeremy J Guza in court for Christine Van Brocklin.  Atty. Guza provides an update; he has all the discovery but needs time to review it with his client as well as receive an offer from the State.  Atty. Guza is requesting a further proceedings date at the beginning of November.  No objection by the State.  Court adjourns for further proceedings.
Hearing scheduled for November 7, 2022 at 10:30 am.

Defendant to have no contact with victim A (or their family) listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney. Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed. Defendant is not to use/possess any drug paraphernalia.

8:40 AM Defendant Christine Van Brocklin in court.  Attorney Jeremy J Guza in court for Christine Van Brocklin.  Attorney Alyssa M Jay in court for State of Wisconsin. 

Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. 
Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. 

The Court notes that attorney Guza filed a Motion to Dismiss.
The State is ready to proceed even on short notice.
The Court will hear the motion.
Attorney Guza presents arguments and requests to grant the Defense's motion and dismiss the case.
ADA Jay presents arguments and requests to deny the Defense's motion.
Attorney Guza presents counter arguments.
The Court places its finding on its record.
The Court finds probable cause and denies the Defense's Motion to Dismiss.
De Novo rights given.

NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED BY COURT.
Hearing scheduled for September 30, 2022 at 10:30 am.
